SIMPLE: inundate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inundate
<hw>In*un"date</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inundated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Inundating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>inundatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>inundare</ets> to inundate; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>undare</ets> to rise in waves, to overflow, fr.
<ets>unda</ets> a wave. See <er>Undulate</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover with a flood; to overflow; to deluge; to
flood; <as>as, the river <ex>inundated</ex> the town</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fill with an overflowing abundance or
superfluity; <as>as, the country was <ex>inundated</ex> with bills of
credit</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To overflow; deluge; flood; overwhelm; submerge;
drown.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inundation</ent>⟦br⟧
